as the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda was born in Aldington, Kent, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Robert Septvans, Knight. She died after 1249."},"et":{"–Aft 1249":"–pärast 1249","1215–1250":"1215–1250","1241–1298":"1241–1298","–1249":"–1249","1249":"1249","1215":"1215","Aft 1249":"pärast 1249","1298":"1298","1241":"1241","1250":"1250","Aldington, Kent, England":"Aldington, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–Aft 1249":"–1249 jälkeen","1215–1250":"1215–1250","1241–1298":"1241–1298","–1249":"–1249","1249":"1249","1215":"1215","Aft 1249":"1249 jälkeen","1298":"1298","1241":"1241","1250":"1250","Aldington, Kent, England":"Aldington, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kent, England":"Kent, Englanti, Yhdistyn